# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: multigrid-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In numerical analysis, a **multigrid method** (**MG method**) is an algorithm for solving differential equations using a hierarchy of discretizations.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] They are an example of a class of techniques called multiresolution methods, very useful in problems exhibiting multiple scales of behavior.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] For example, many basic relaxation methods exhibit different rates of convergence for short- and long-wavelength components, suggesting these different scales be treated differently, as in a Fourier analysis approach to multigrid.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] MG methods can be used as solvers as well as preconditioners.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The main idea of multigrid is to accelerate the convergence of a basic iterative method (known as relaxation, which generally reduces short-wavelength error) by a *global* correction of the fine grid solution approximation from time to time, accomplished by solving a coarse problem.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The coarse problem, while cheaper to solve, is similar to the fine grid problem in that it also has short- and long-wavelength errors.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] It can also be solved by a combination of relaxation and appeal to still coarser grids.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] This recursive process is repeated until a grid is reached where the cost of direct solution there is negligible compared to the cost of one relaxation sweep on the fine grid.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] This multigrid cycle typically reduces all error components by a fixed amount bounded well below one, independent of the fine grid mesh size.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The typical application for multigrid is in the numerical solution of elliptic partial differential equations in two or more dimensions.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Multigrid methods can be applied in combination with any of the common discretization techniques.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] For example, the finite element method may be recast as a multigrid method.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In these cases, multigrid methods are among the fastest solution techniques known today.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In contrast to other methods, multigrid methods are general in that they can treat arbitrary regions and boundary conditions.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] They do not depend on the separability of the equations or other special properties of the equation.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] They have also been widely used for more-complicated non-symmetric and nonlinear systems of equations, like the Lamé equations of elasticity or the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] There are many variations of multigrid algorithms, but the common features are that a hierarchy of discretizations (grids) is considered.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] There are many choices of multigrid methods with varying trade-offs between speed of solving a single iteration and the rate of convergence with said iteration.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The 3 main types are V-Cycle, F-Cycle, and W-Cycle.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] These differ in which and how many coarse-grain cycles are performed per fine iteration.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The V-Cycle algorithm executes one coarse-grain V-Cycle.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] F-Cycle does a coarse-grain V-Cycle followed by a coarse-grain F-Cycle, while each W-Cycle performs two coarse-grain W-Cycles per iteration.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] For a discrete 2D problem, F-Cycle takes 83% more time to compute than a V-Cycle iteration while a W-Cycle iteration takes 125% more.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] If the problem is set up in a 3D domain, then a F-Cycle iteration and a W-Cycle iteration take about 64% and 75% more time respectively than a V-Cycle iteration ignoring overheads.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Typically, W-Cycle produces similar convergence to F-Cycle.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] However, in cases of convection-diffusion problems with high Péclet numbers, W-Cycle can show superiority in its rate of convergence per iteration over F-Cycle.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The choice of smoothing operators are extremely diverse as they include Krylov subspace methods and can be preconditioned.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Any geometric multigrid cycle iteration is performed on a hierarchy of grids and hence it can be coded using recursion.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Since the function calls itself with smaller sized (coarser) parameters, the coarsest grid is where the recursion stops.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In cases where the system has a high condition number, the correction procedure is modified such that only a fraction of the prolongated coarser grid solution is added onto the finer grid.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] This approach has the advantage over other methods that it often scales linearly with the number of discrete nodes used.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In other words, it can solve these problems to a given accuracy in a number of operations that is proportional to the number of unknowns.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Assume that one has a differential equation which can be solved approximately (with a given accuracy) on a grid i with a given grid point density $N_{i}$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Assume furthermore that a solution on any grid $N_{i}$ may be obtained with a given effort $W_{i}=\rho KN_{i}$ from a solution on a coarser grid $i+1$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Here, $\rho =N_{i+1}/N_{i}<1$ is the ratio of grid points on "neighboring" grids and is assumed to be constant throughout the grid hierarchy, and K is some constant modeling the effort of computing the result for one grid point.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] that is, a solution may be obtained in $O(N)$ time.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] It should be mentioned that there is one exception to the $O(N)$ i.e.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] W-cycle multigrid used on a 1D problem; it would result in $O(N\log N)$ complexity.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] A multigrid method with an intentionally reduced tolerance can be used as an efficient preconditioner for an external iterative solver, e.g., The solution may still be obtained in $O(N)$ time as well as in the case where the multigrid method is used as a solver.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Multigrid preconditioning is used in practice even for linear systems, typically with one cycle per iteration, e.g., in Hypre.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Its main advantage versus a purely multigrid solver is particularly clear for nonlinear problems, e.g., eigenvalue problems.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] If the matrix of the original equation or an eigenvalue problem is symmetric positive definite (SPD), the preconditioner is commonly constructed to be SPD as well, so that the standard conjugate gradient (CG) iterative methods can still be used.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Such imposed SPD constraints may complicate the construction of the preconditioner, e.g., requiring coordinated pre- and post-smoothing.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] However, preconditioned steepest descent and flexible CG methods for SPD linear systems and LOBPCG for symmetric eigenvalue problems are all shown to be robust if the preconditioner is not SPD.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In view of the subspace correction framework, BPX preconditioner is a parallel subspace correction method whereas the classic V-cycle is a successive subspace correction method.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The BPX-preconditioner is known to be naturally more parallel and in some applications more robust than the classic V-cycle multigrid method.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The method has been widely used by researchers and practitioners since 1990.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Multigrid methods can be generalized in many different ways.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] They can be applied naturally in a time-stepping solution of parabolic partial differential equations, or they can be applied directly to time-dependent partial differential equations.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Research on multilevel techniques for hyperbolic partial differential equations is underway.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Multigrid methods can also be applied to integral equations, or for problems in statistical physics.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Another set of multiresolution methods is based upon wavelets.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] These wavelet methods can be combined with multigrid methods.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] For example, one use of wavelets is to reformulate the finite element approach in terms of a multilevel method.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Practically important extensions of multigrid methods include techniques where no partial differential equation nor geometrical problem background is used to construct the multilevel hierarchy.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Such **algebraic multigrid methods** (AMG) construct their hierarchy of operators directly from the system matrix.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In classical AMG, the levels of the hierarchy are simply subsets of unknowns without any geometric interpretation.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] (More generally, coarse grid unknowns can be particular linear combinations of fine grid unknowns.) Thus, AMG methods become black-box solvers for certain classes of sparse matrices.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] AMG is regarded as advantageous mainly where geometric multigrid is too difficult to apply, but is often used simply because it avoids the coding necessary for a true multigrid implementation.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] While classical AMG was developed first, a related algebraic method is known as smoothed aggregation (SA).
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] In an overview paper by Jinchao Xu and Ludmil Zikatanov, the "algebraic multigrid" methods are understood from an abstract point of view.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] They developed a unified framework and existing algebraic multigrid methods can be derived coherently.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Abstract theory about how to construct optimal coarse space as well as quasi-optimal spaces was derived.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] We note that this result appeared first in a note on Algebraic Multigrid by Brannick and Zikatanov and was just rewritten in the overview paper.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Also, they proved that, under appropriate assumptions, the abstract two-level AMG method converges uniformly with respect to the size of the linear system, the coefficient variation, and the anisotropy.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Their abstract framework covers most existing AMG methods, such as classical AMG, energy-minimization AMG, unsmoothed and smoothed aggregation AMG, and spectral AMGe.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Multigrid methods have also been adopted for the solution of initial value problems.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Of particular interest here are parallel-in-time multigrid methods: in contrast to classical Runge–Kutta or linear multistep methods, they can offer concurrency in temporal direction.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] The well known Parareal parallel-in-time integration method can also be reformulated as a two-level multigrid in time.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Nearly singular problems arise in a number of important physical and engineering applications.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Simple, but important example of nearly singular problems can be found at the displacement formulation of linear elasticity for nearly incompressible materials.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Typically, the major problem to solve such nearly singular systems boils down to treat the nearly singular operator given by $A+\varepsilon M$ robustly with respect to the positive, but small parameter $\varepsilon$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] Here A is symmetric semidefinite operator with large null space, while M is a symmetric positive definite operator.
[src:multigrid-methods/algebraic-multigrid-method] There were many works to attempt to design a robust and fast multigrid method for such nearly singular problems.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] In mathematics, numerical analysis, and numerical partial differential equations, **domain decomposition methods** solve a boundary value problem by splitting it into smaller boundary value problems on subdomains and iterating to coordinate the solution between adjacent subdomains.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] A coarse problem with one or few unknowns per subdomain is used to further coordinate the solution between the subdomains globally.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] The problems on the subdomains are independent, which makes domain decomposition methods suitable for parallel computing.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Domain decomposition methods are typically used as preconditioners for Krylov space iterative methods, such as the conjugate gradient method, GMRES, and LOBPCG.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] In overlapping domain decomposition methods, the subdomains overlap by more than the interface.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Overlapping domain decomposition methods include the Schwarz alternating method and the additive Schwarz method.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Many domain decomposition methods can be written and analyzed as a special case of the abstract additive Schwarz method.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] In non-overlapping methods, the subdomains intersect only on their interface.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] In primal methods, such as Balancing domain decomposition and BDDC, the continuity of the solution across subdomain interface is enforced by representing the value of the solution on all neighboring subdomains by the same unknown.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] In dual methods, such as FETI, the continuity of the solution across the subdomain interface is enforced by Lagrange multipliers.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] The FETI-DP method is hybrid between a dual and a primal method.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Non-overlapping domain decomposition methods are also called **iterative substructuring methods**.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Mortar methods are discretization methods for partial differential equations, which use separate discretization on nonoverlapping subdomains.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] The meshes on the subdomains do not match on the interface, and the equality of the solution is enforced by Lagrange multipliers, judiciously chosen to preserve the accuracy of the solution.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] In the engineering practice in the finite element method, continuity of solutions between non-matching subdomains is implemented by multiple-point constraints.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Finite element simulations of moderate size models require solving linear systems with millions of unknowns.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Several hours per time step is an average sequential run time, therefore, parallel computing is a necessity.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Domain decomposition methods embody large potential for a parallelization of the finite element methods, and serve a basis for distributed, parallel computations.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Domain decomposition methods have been successfully applied to problems ranging from fluid dynamics to elastic simulations.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] Several studies investigated the decomposition of computational or discretization domains into multiple subdomains and analyzed the resulting discretized couplings independently.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] The standard and optimized Schwarz methods have been used also in the context of mesh smoothing, concretely in the process of mean curvature flow for general polygonal meshes.
[src:multigrid-methods/domain-decomposition-methods] In the left subdomain define the interpolating function $v_{1}(x)$ and in the right define $v_{2}(x)$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] In numerical linear algebra, the **Gauss–Seidel method**, also known as the **Liebmann method** or the **method of successive displacement**, is an iterative method used to solve a system of linear equations.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] It is named after the German mathematicians Carl Friedrich Gauss and Philipp Ludwig von Seidel.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Though it can be applied to any matrix with non-zero elements on the diagonals, convergence is only guaranteed if the matrix is either strictly diagonally dominant, or symmetric and positive definite.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] It was only mentioned in a private letter from Gauss to his student Gerling in 1823.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] A publication was not delivered before 1874 by Seidel.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] When $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ are known, and $\mathbf {x}$ is unknown, the Gauss–Seidel method can be used to iteratively approximate $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Denote by $\mathbf {x} ^{(k)}$ the k -th approximation or iteration of $\mathbf {x}$ , and by $\mathbf {x} ^{(k+1)}$ the approximation of $\mathbf {x}$ at the next (or $k+1$ -th) iteration.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] The Gauss–Seidel method now solves the left hand side of this expression for **$\mathbf {x}$**, using the previous value for **$\mathbf {x}$** on the right hand side.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Notice that the formula uses two summations per iteration which can be expressed as one summation $\sum _{j\neq i}a_{ij}x_{j}$ that uses the most recently calculated iteration of $x_{j}$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] The procedure is generally continued until the changes made by an iteration are below some tolerance, such as a sufficiently small residual.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] In Gauss-Seidel, the computation of $\mathbf {x} ^{(k+1)}$ uses the elements of $\mathbf {x} ^{(k+1)}$ that have already been computed, and only the elements of $\mathbf {x} ^{(k)}$ that have not been computed in the $(k+1)$ -th iteration.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] This means that, unlike the Jacobi method, only one storage vector is required as elements can be overwritten as they are computed, which can be advantageous for very large problems.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] However, unlike the Jacobi method, the computations for each element are generally much harder to implement in parallel, since they can have a very long critical path, and are thus most feasible for sparse matrices.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Furthermore, the values at each iteration are dependent on the order of the original equations.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Gauss-Seidel is the same as successive over-relaxation with $\omega =1$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] The convergence properties of the Gauss–Seidel method are dependent on the matrix $\mathbf {A}$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] The Gauss–Seidel method may converge even if these conditions are not satisfied.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Golub and Van Loan give a theorem for an algorithm that splits $\mathbf {A}$ into two parts.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Suppose $\mathbf {A} =\mathbf {M} -\mathbf {N}$ is nonsingular.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Since elements can be overwritten as they are computed in this algorithm, only one storage vector is needed, and vector indexing is omitted.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] With $\mathbf {T}$ and $\mathbf {c}$ the vectors $\mathbf {x}$ can be obtained iteratively.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] First of all, choose $\mathbf {x} ^{(0)}$ , for example $\mathbf {x} ^{(0)}={\begin{bmatrix}1.0\\1.0\end{bmatrix}}.$ The closer the guess to the final solution, the fewer iterations the algorithm will need.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] In fact, the matrix A is strictly diagonally dominant, but not positive definite.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] In a test for convergence we find that the algorithm diverges.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] In fact, the matrix $\mathbf {A}$ is neither diagonally dominant nor positive definite.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Then, convergence to the exact solution $\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {A} ^{-1}\mathbf {b} ={\begin{bmatrix}-38\\29\end{bmatrix}}$ is not guaranteed and, in this case, will not occur.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Suppose given n equations and a starting point $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] At any step in a Gauss-Seidel iteration, solve the first equation for $x_{1}$ in terms of $x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}$ ; then solve the second equation for $x_{2}$ in terms of $x_{1}$ just found and the remaining $x_{3},\dots ,x_{n}$ ; and continue to $x_{n}$ .
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Then, repeat iterations until convergence is achieved, or break if the divergence in the solutions start to diverge beyond a predefined level.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] Using the approximations obtained, the iterative procedure is repeated until the desired accuracy has been reached.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] The following are the approximated solutions after four iterations.
[src:multigrid-methods/gauss-seidel-method] The exact solution of the system is (1, 2, −1, 1).
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] In computational mathematics, an **iterative method** is a mathematical procedure that uses an initial value to generate a sequence of improving approximate solutions for a class of problems, in which the *i*-th approximation (called an "iterate") is derived from the previous ones.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] A specific implementation with termination criteria for a given iterative method like gradient descent, hill climbing, Newton's method, or quasi-Newton methods like BFGS, is an algorithm of an iterative method or a **method of successive approximation**.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] An iterative method is called *convergent* if the corresponding sequence converges for given initial approximations.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] A mathematically rigorous convergence analysis of an iterative method is usually performed; however, heuristic-based iterative methods are also common.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] In contrast, **direct methods** attempt to solve the problem by a finite sequence of operations.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] In the absence of rounding errors, direct methods would deliver an exact solution (for example, solving a linear system of equations $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ by Gaussian elimination).
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Iterative methods are often the only choice for nonlinear equations.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] However, iterative methods are often useful even for linear problems involving many variables (sometimes on the order of millions), where direct methods would be prohibitively expensive (and in some cases impossible) even with the best available computing power.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Here *x**n* is the *n*th approximation or iteration of *x* and *x**n*+1 is the next or *n* + 1 iteration of *x*.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Alternately, superscripts in parentheses are often used in numerical methods, so as not to interfere with subscripts with other meanings.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] (For example, *x*(*n*+1) = *f*(*x*(*n*)).) If the function *f* is continuously differentiable, a sufficient condition for convergence is that the spectral radius of the derivative is strictly bounded by one in a neighborhood of the fixed point.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] If this condition holds at the fixed point, then a sufficiently small neighborhood (basin of attraction) must exist.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] In the case of a system of linear equations, the two main classes of iterative methods are the **stationary iterative methods**, and the more general Krylov subspace methods.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Stationary iterative methods solve a linear system with an operator approximating the original one; and based on a measurement of the error in the result (the residual), form a "correction equation" for which this process is repeated.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] While these methods are simple to derive, implement, and analyze, convergence is only guaranteed for a limited class of matrices.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] The basic iterative methods work by splitting the matrix A into $A=M-N$ and here the matrix M should be easily invertible.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Basic examples of stationary iterative methods use a splitting of the matrix A such as $A=D+L+U\,,\quad D:=\operatorname {diag} ((a_{ii})_{i})$ where D is only the diagonal part of A , and L is the strict lower triangular part of A .
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Respectively, U is the strict upper triangular part of A .
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Linear stationary iterative methods are also called relaxation methods.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Krylov subspace methods work by forming a basis of the sequence of successive matrix powers times the initial residual (the **Krylov sequence**).
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] The approximations to the solution are then formed by minimizing the residual over the subspace formed.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] The prototypical method in this class is the conjugate gradient method (CG) which assumes that the system matrix A is symmetric positive-definite.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] For symmetric (and possibly indefinite) A one works with the minimal residual method (MINRES).
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] In the case of non-symmetric matrices, methods such as the generalized minimal residual method (GMRES) and the biconjugate gradient method (BiCG) have been derived.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Since these methods form a basis, it is evident that the method converges in *N* iterations, where *N* is the system size.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] However, in the presence of rounding errors this statement does not hold; moreover, in practice *N* can be very large, and the iterative process reaches sufficient accuracy already far earlier.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] The analysis of these methods is hard, depending on a complicated function of the spectrum of the operator.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] The construction of preconditioners is a large research area.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Jamshīd al-Kāshī used iterative methods to calculate the sine of 1° and π in *The Treatise of Chord and Sine* to high precision.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] An early iterative method for solving a linear system appeared in a letter of Gauss to a student of his.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] He proposed solving a 4-by-4 system of equations by repeatedly solving the component in which the residual was the largest .
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] The theory of stationary iterative methods was solidly established with the work of D.M.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] The conjugate gradient method was also invented in the 1950s, with independent developments by Cornelius Lanczos, Magnus Hestenes and Eduard Stiefel, but its nature and applicability were misunderstood at the time.
[src:multigrid-methods/iterative-method] Only in the 1970s was it realized that conjugacy based methods work very well for partial differential equations, especially the elliptic type.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] In numerical mathematics, **relaxation methods** are iterative methods for solving systems of equations, including nonlinear systems.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] Relaxation methods were developed for solving large sparse linear systems, which arose as finite-difference discretizations of differential equations.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] They are also used for the solution of linear equations for linear least-squares problems and also for systems of linear inequalities, such as those arising in linear programming.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] They have also been developed for solving nonlinear systems of equations.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] Relaxation methods are important especially in the solution of linear systems used to model elliptic partial differential equations, such as Laplace's equation and its generalization, Poisson's equation.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] These equations describe boundary-value problems, in which the solution-function's values are specified on boundary of a domain; the problem is to compute a solution also on its interior.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] Relaxation methods are used to solve the linear equations resulting from a discretization of the differential equation, for example by finite differences.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] Iterative relaxation of solutions is commonly dubbed smoothing because with certain equations, such as Laplace's equation, it resembles repeated application of a local smoothing filter to the solution vector.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] These are not to be confused with relaxation methods in mathematical optimization, which approximate a difficult problem by a simpler problem whose "relaxed" solution provides information about the solution of the original problem.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] The method is easily generalized to other numbers of dimensions.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] While the method converges under general conditions, it typically makes slower progress than competing methods.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] Nonetheless, the study of relaxation methods remains a core part of linear algebra, because the transformations of relaxation theory provide excellent preconditioners for new methods.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] Indeed, the choice of preconditioner is often more important than the choice of iterative method.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] Multigrid methods may be used to accelerate the methods.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] One can first compute an approximation on a coarser grid – usually the double spacing 2*h* – and use that solution with interpolated values for the other grid points as the initial assignment.
[src:multigrid-methods/relaxation-iterative-method] This can then also be done recursively for the coarser computation.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] In numerical linear algebra, the method of **successive over-relaxation** (**SOR**) is a variant of the Gauss–Seidel method for solving a linear system of equations, resulting in faster convergence.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] A similar method can be used for any slowly converging iterative process.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] It was devised simultaneously by David M.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] Frankel in 1950 for the purpose of automatically solving linear systems on digital computers.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] Over-relaxation methods had been used before the work of Young and Frankel.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] An example is the method of Lewis Fry Richardson, and the methods developed by R.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] However, these methods were designed for computation by human calculators, requiring some expertise to ensure convergence to the solution which made them inapplicable for programming on digital computers.
