[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] Values of $\omega >1$ are used to speed up convergence of a slow-converging process, while values of $\omega <1$ are often used to help establish convergence of a diverging iterative process or speed up the convergence of an overshooting process.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] There are various methods that adaptively set the relaxation parameter $\omega$ based on the observed behavior of the converging process.
[src:multigrid-methods/successive-over-relaxation] Usually they help to reach a super-linear convergence for some problems but fail for the others.
